# 🔐 Vault Pricing Strategy – Item-Based Model

## 🧭 Overview

This pricing model is based on **limiting the number of vault items** a user can store.

It is designed to be:
- Simple
- Easy to understand
- Easy to enforce
- Effective for conversion

---

## 🎯 Core Model

### 🟢 Free Plan
- Store up to **8 vault items**
- Full encryption (never restricted)
- Core vault functionality
- Local storage + manual backup

---

### 🔵 Pro Plan (€4–€6/month OR €30–€50/year)
- Store up to **64 vault items**
- Advanced credential types (API keys, SSH, tokens)
- Encrypted file attachments
- Advanced search & tagging
- Recovery system
- Auto-lock & session controls

---

## ⚠️ Why NOT 4 Items?

Originally considered:
- Free → 4 items

**Problem:**
- Too restrictive
- Users don’t experience enough value
- Lower trust and conversion

---

## ✅ Why 8 Items Works Better

- Enough for real usage (email, bank, 2–3 accounts, API key, etc.)
- Users experience product value
- Still creates upgrade pressure

---

## 💡 Positioning (Important)

Avoid negative phrasing:

❌ “Limited to 8 items”  
✅ “Store up to 8 secure items”

---

## 🚀 Upgrade Triggers

### Hard Limit Reached

Show:

> “You’ve reached your secure item limit.  
Upgrade to Pro to store up to 64 items and unlock advanced features.”

---

### Soft Warning (Recommended at ~75%)

Example:

> “You’re using 6 of 8 secure items.”

**Why:**
- Prepares users psychologically
- Increases conversion rates

---

## 🧩 What Counts as an Item

Vault items include:
- Login credentials
- API keys
- Secure notes
- Tokens / secrets

Do NOT count:
- Settings
- System metadata
- Internal vault configuration

---

## 🧠 Why Item Limits Work

- Each item has high perceived value
- Feels fair (not arbitrary)
- Encourages structured usage
- Natural upgrade path

---

## 🆚 Competitive Context

| Product | Free Limit |
|--------|-----------|
| Bitwarden | Unlimited |
| KeePass | Unlimited |
| 1Password | No free plan |
